{
  "title": "Self-Consistent Blind Source Separation for Iterative Lensing Reconstruction",
  "summary": "This research proposes an iterative, blind source separation method to reconstruct the CMB lensing potential by treating the lensing signal as a non-Gaussian perturbation. By exploiting off-diagonal correlations in the CMB covariance matrix, the approach enables lensing inversion without relying on external tracers.",
  "method": "The implementation uses a Maximum A Posteriori (MAP) estimation framework, starting with a Gaussian simulation baseline. An initial lensing potential estimate is obtained via a quadratic estimator, followed by an iterative cycle of delensing the map, re-estimating the power spectrum, and refining the potential from residuals until the lensing power spectrum converges.",
  "expected_outcome": "The project aims to retrieve a lensing power spectrum consistent with Planck 2018 cosmological parameters using only internal map statistics. Success will be measured by a reconstructed lensing potential map with reduced noise levels and a higher correlation coefficient compared to standard quadratic estimators."
}

{
  "feasibility": "The proposal faces significant challenges because iterative MAP estimation provides only marginal gains for temperature-only data due to cosmic variance limits. Furthermore, the method lacks a strategy to handle non-Gaussian extragalactic foregrounds like CIB and tSZ, which will likely be misidentified as lensing signals.",
  "novelty": "The idea is highly derivative; rebranding iterative MAP lensing reconstruction as 'blind source separation' does not constitute a new concept, as the underlying methodology has been well-established since 2003.",
  "constraints_respected": true,
  "fixes": [
    "Remove the 'blind source separation' terminology unless integrating a specific ICA-like algorithm with detailed interaction mechanics.",
    "Incorporate a concrete mitigation strategy for non-Gaussian temperature foregrounds, such as bias-hardened estimators or profile marginalization.",
    "Explicitly differentiate the proposed algorithm from existing pipelines like plancklens or symlens by identifying a specific novel algorithmic twist."
  ]
}

{
  "title": "Bias-Hardened Reconstruction via Non-Gaussian Gradient Templates for Temperature-Only Lensing",
  "summary": "This proposal introduces a bias-hardened quadratic estimator that specifically targets and subtracts non-Gaussian foreground templates, such as the Cosmic Infrared Background (CIB) and Sunyaev-Zel'dovich (SZ) effect, directly from the map using local spatial profiles. Unlike standard estimators that treat non-Gaussian foregrounds as noise, this method treats them as deterministic, localized signals to be subtracted before the lensing reconstruction phase, effectively decoupling foreground contamination from the weak lensing signal.",
  "method": "I will implement a two-stage pipeline. In the first stage, I will apply a matched filter algorithm to the map to generate templates of known non-Gaussian foreground profiles (specifically tSZ clusters and point sources identified by brightness peaks). In the second stage, I will construct a modified quadratic estimator that incorporates \"bias-hardened\" kernels, which are mathematically orthogonalized against the specific derivative templates of these foreground profiles. This ensures that the lensing reconstruction operator yields a zero-response to the foreground signals identified in the first stage, rather than simply suppressing them, thereby preventing foreground leakage into the lensing potential estimate.",
  "expected_outcome": "I expect to demonstrate a reduction in the reconstruction bias (the \"foreground contamination\") that typically plagues temperature-only estimators, verified by a decrease in the cross-correlation between the reconstructed lensing potential and the identified foreground masks. The success metric will be a statistically significant improvement in the signal-to-noise ratio of the lensing potential power spectrum at high multipoles (L > 500), where foreground interference currently limits traditional Planck-like estimators."
}

{
  "feasibility": "The approach faces significant challenges due to the single-map constraint, which prevents effective component separation. Identifying foregrounds like tSZ and CIB from a single map is prone to high error rates, and the proposed validation metric is circular. Furthermore, bias-hardening on a single map is likely to cause excessive variance inflation, destroying the signal-to-noise ratio.",
  "novelty": "The idea is not novel. The concept of bias-hardened quadratic estimators is well-established in literature (e.g., Osborne et al. 2014, Sailer et al. 2020), and the proposed internal template generation does not sufficiently differentiate the approach from existing techniques.",
  "constraints_respected": true,
  "fixes": [
    "Replace the circular validation metric with a suite of mock single-frequency maps containing injected lensing and realistic foregrounds to measure residual bias.",
    "Shift focus from deterministic templating of resolved sources to statistical bias-hardening against unresolved non-Gaussian backgrounds using higher-order statistics like the CIB trispectrum.",
    "Incorporate a penalty or regularization term into the quadratic estimator to mitigate variance inflation caused by bias-hardening on a single map."
  ]
}
